TITLE & AUTHORS
================================================================================

**LLM-ERP: Architecture and Implementation of an LLM-Driven Intelligent Enterprise Resource Planning System**

Peter Fan, *Independent Researcher*

Corresponding author: Peter Fan (e-mail: pok59420@gmail.com)
ORCID: [To be registered]

================================================================================
ABSTRACT
================================================================================

Traditional Enterprise Resource Planning (ERP) systems rely on menu-driven navigation with transaction codes, requiring months of training and creating high barriers to user adoption. This paper presents LLM-ERP, an open-source intelligent ERP system that replaces the traditional interface with natural language interaction powered by Large Language Models (LLMs). The system spans six manufacturing modules—inventory management, procurement, BOM/engineering, production dispatch, quality management, and financial accounting—unified under a single conversational interface with role-adaptive dashboards. Key technical contributions include: (1) a 27-tool function-calling architecture covering the full ERP lifecycle, (2) a 22-rule proactive constraint engine that intercepts invalid operations before execution, (3) an event-driven cross-functional notification system with role-based routing, and (4) a real-time War Room visualization for multi-screen factory monitoring. Experimental evaluation with 30 natural language test queries across all modules achieved 90% end-to-end accuracy and 100% data validation pass rate using DeepSeek, with an average response time of 7.7 seconds—representing a 4-15× speed improvement over traditional GUI-based ERP workflows. The complete system is released as open source to enable community adoption and academic reproducibility.

*Keywords*—ERP, Large Language Model, LLM Agent, Function Calling, Intelligent Manufacturing, Industry 4.0, Natural Language Interface, Proactive Constraint Enforcement

================================================================================
I. INTRODUCTION
================================================================================

Enterprise Resource Planning (ERP) systems form the digital backbone of modern manufacturing operations, managing everything from procurement and inventory to production scheduling and financial accounting. Despite decades of evolution, mainstream ERP solutions (SAP S/4HANA, Oracle JD Edwards, Odoo) share a fundamental interaction paradigm: menu-driven navigation with transaction codes. A user creating a purchase order in SAP must navigate through path `Logistics → Materials Management → Purchasing → Purchase Order → Create → Vendor/Supplying Plant Known`, or memorize the T-code `ME21N`. This paradigm imposes several well-documented limitations.

**High learning curves.** ERP training typically requires 3-6 months for proficient operation [1]. The Gartner 2023 ERP survey reported that 47% of organizations cite "user adoption difficulty" as a top implementation barrier [2]. Users develop workarounds—spreadsheets, sticky notes, shadow systems—to bypass rigid interfaces [3].

**Static, open-loop scheduling.** Traditional ERP executes Material Requirements Planning (MRP) in batch mode, generating static production plans that assume infinite capacity and ignore real-time shop floor disruptions [4]. When a machine breaks down or a rush order arrives, the planner must manually reschedule—a process that takes hours and often results in suboptimal decisions [5].

**Limited cross-functional visibility.** ERP modules evolved as isolated silos (MM, PP, QM, FI). While modern suites offer integrated databases, the user experience remains fragmented—a warehouse keeper cannot see the purchasing impact of their receipt transaction without switching screens [6].

The emergence of Large Language Models (LLMs) with function-calling capabilities—such as GPT-4 [7], Claude [8], and DeepSeek—presents a new interaction paradigm. Rather than navigating menus, users can express intent in natural language, and the LLM translates that intent into structured API calls against the ERP backend. This approach has been explored in limited contexts (NL2SQL for database queries [9], conversational interfaces for CRM [10]), but a comprehensive architecture spanning six ERP modules with proactive constraint enforcement and event-driven cross-functional coordination has not been demonstrated.

**Contributions.** This paper presents LLM-ERP, an open-source intelligent ERP system with the following contributions:

1. A six-module LLM-ERP architecture covering inventory (MM), procurement (PP), BOM/engineering, production dispatch (PP), quality management (QM), and financial accounting (FI), unified under a natural language interface.
2. A proactive constraint engine with 22 business rules that intercept invalid operations before execution—covering material availability, capacity feasibility, quality locks, double-entry accounting, and month-end close enforcement.
3. A cross-functional notification engine implementing a publish-subscribe event model with role-based routing, ensuring that domain events reach all affected roles through in-app, War Room, and Telegram channels.
4. A War Room visualization providing a real-time value stream display with animated event flow across six manufacturing stages, designed for multi-monitor factory floor deployment.
5. Experimental evaluation with 30 natural language test queries across all modules, achieving 90% end-to-end accuracy and 100% data validation with the DeepSeek provider at an average response time of 7.7 seconds—representing a 4-15× speed improvement over traditional GUI-based ERP workflows.

================================================================================
II. RELATED WORK
================================================================================

**A. ERP System Limitations**

Davenport [1] identified the fundamental tension between ERP's promise of integration and the organizational misfits that arise when a standardized system meets unique business processes. Markus and Tanis [11] documented that ERP projects consistently exceed budget and schedule, with user training consuming 15-25% of total implementation cost. Soh et al. [3] provided empirical evidence of cultural misfits, showing that Asian manufacturing firms using Western ERP packages developed extensive workarounds for functionality gaps in areas like subcontracting and multi-currency transactions.

Gattiker and Goodhue [12] analyzed the post-implementation period, finding that operational benefits emerge only after 12-18 months as users develop proficiency—a timeline that many small-to-medium enterprises (SMEs) cannot sustain. Hong and Kim [13] identified organizational fit as the single strongest predictor of ERP implementation success, measured by user satisfaction and operational performance.

**B. Advanced Planning and Scheduling**

Production scheduling in ERP follows the MRPII paradigm: MPS (Master Production Schedule) → MRP (Material Requirements Planning) → CRP (Capacity Requirements Planning) [14]. This waterfall approach assumes deterministic lead times and infinite capacity, producing schedules that are infeasible in practice [4].

Advanced Planning and Scheduling (APS) systems address these limitations through mathematical optimization. Pinedo [15] provides a comprehensive taxonomy of scheduling problems—job shop, flow shop, open shop—each with distinct complexity characteristics (NP-hard in most cases). Allahverdi [16] surveyed setup time considerations in scheduling, finding that setup-dependent sequencing can improve makespan by 15-30%.

Dynamic rescheduling research has explored three strategies for handling disruptions: right-shift (delaying affected operations), route change (rerouting to alternate resources), and expedite (priority reordering). Xiong et al. [5] provide a comprehensive survey, noting that most approaches assume a single disruption type and perfect disruption information—assumptions that rarely hold in practice.

Recent work in deep reinforcement learning (DRL) for scheduling [17, 18] shows promise but requires extensive training data per factory configuration and struggles with generalization across different product mixes. LLM-ERP takes a complementary approach: rather than optimizing schedules automatically, it assists human planners through natural language, leaving strategic decisions to domain experts while automating routine information retrieval and constraint validation.

**C. LLMs in Enterprise Software**

Schick et al. [19] introduced Toolformer, demonstrating that LLMs can learn to use APIs through self-supervised fine-tuning. Yao et al. [20] proposed ReAct, a prompting framework that interleaves reasoning traces with action execution—achieving strong results on knowledge-intensive QA and decision-making benchmarks.

Several works have applied LLMs to database access. Iyer et al. [9] demonstrated that GPT-4 achieves 87% accuracy on enterprise NL2SQL benchmarks, though accuracy drops significantly (to 62%) when queries involve temporal reasoning or multi-table joins—common in ERP contexts.

HuggingGPT [21] and AutoGen [22] explored multi-agent architectures where specialized agents handle different domains. MetaGPT [23] introduced a software development meta-agent that decomposes requirements into subtasks—an architecture that inspired LLM-ERP's cross-module workflow design.

Most relevant is the work by Yang et al. [24] on LLM-assisted BOM management in ERP systems, which demonstrated that LLMs can perform multi-level BOM explosion and shortage detection with 85% accuracy. However, their system was limited to a single module and did not address the broader challenge of cross-functional ERP workflows.

**Research gap.** The literature lacks an end-to-end implementation of an LLM-driven ERP system spanning multiple manufacturing modules with proactive constraint enforcement, cross-functional notifications, and quantitative evaluation against real enterprise data. LLM-ERP addresses this gap.

================================================================================
III. SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE
================================================================================

**A. System Architecture Overview**

The proposed LLM-ERP system follows a four-tier architecture: a Role-Adaptive Frontend (React + TypeScript), an LLM Orchestrator (Python FastAPI with multi-provider support), a Domain Service Layer, and an Event Engine cross-cutting all layers. Unlike traditional ERP systems where users navigate rigid menu hierarchies and memorize transaction codes, LLM-ERP presents a unified natural language interface augmented by role-specific dashboards.

The system is decomposed into six operational modules plus one cross-cutting component:

[Table 1: System Modules]

| Module | Abbr. | Core Functions |
|--------|-------|----------------|
| Inventory | MM | Parts master, stock query, inbound/outbound, location management |
| Purchase | PP | Supplier management, PO lifecycle (draft→sent→received→closed) |
| BOM | PP/ENG | Product structure, multi-level explosion, shortage detection |
| Dispatch | PP/MFG | Work order lifecycle, work center management, dynamic rescheduling |
| Quality | QM | Inspection orders, NC tracking, CAPA management |
| Accounting | FI | Chart of accounts, journal entries, AR/AP, month-end close |
| Event Engine | — | Pub-sub notifications, constraint enforcement, role routing |

**B. User Archetype Definition**

We define six core user archetypes for manufacturing ERP. Each archetype is characterized by their primary concern, decision-making level (following Anthony's framework [25]), LLM interaction mode, and notification scope:

[Table 2: User Archetypes]

| Archetype | Role | Concern | Decision Level | LLM Mode |
|-----------|------|---------|----------------|----------|
| U_d | Factory Director | Plant-wide KPI, exceptions | Strategic | Summarize trends |
| U_p | Production Controller | Schedule, material shortage | Tactical | What-if simulation |
| U_w | Warehouse Keeper | Picking, receiving, inventory | Operational | Command-driven |
| U_b | Purchasing Agent | PO lifecycle, supplier cost | Tactical | Multi-vendor comparison |
| U_q | Quality Inspector | Inspection, NC, CAPA | Operational/Analytic | Defect analysis |
| U_a | Accountant/CFO | Cash flow, AR/AP, cost | Strategic/Tactical | Forecast, payment recommendation |

Each archetype's interface is a subset of a unified component library. Formally, given a widget set W and role r, the visible dashboard D_r is defined by a role-widget mapping M: R → P(W).

**C. Domain Module Design**

**Inventory Module (MM):** Manages parts master data (12 seed items), stock levels with location tracking, and material movements. Inbound (material.received) increments stock against PO reference; outbound (material.issued) decrements stock and triggers constraint checks.

**Purchase Module (PP):** Full procurement lifecycle from supplier management (score-based evaluation) to PO lifecycle (draft → sent → partially_received → received → closed). Multi-line POs with part, quantity, price per line item. PO receipt auto-triggers inventory inbound and accounting AP entry.

**BOM Module (PP/ENG):** Multi-level product structure with recursive parent-child relationships. Supports BOM explosion (flattening all sub-component requirements) and shortage detection (BOM requirements vs. on-hand inventory comparison).

**Dispatch Module (PP/MFG):** Work center management (idle/running/down/maintenance), production order lifecycle (draft → released → dispatched → in_progress → completed → closed), operation sequencing, and three dynamic rescheduling strategies: right_shift (delay), route_change (alternate work center), expedite (priority boost).

**Quality Module (QM):** Four-table closed-loop quality management: inspection_orders (triggered by inbound receipt), inspection_results (measurements), non_conformances (NCs with severity), capa_records (corrective/preventive actions). NCs lock associated stock; CAPA closure unlocks it.

**Accounting Module (FI):** Double-entry bookkeeping with five tables: accounts (chart of accounts), journal_entries (GL posting header), journal_lines (debit/credit enforced), accounts_receivable (aging), month_end_closes (period locking). AR aging computed dynamically (current, 1-30, 31-60, 60+ days overdue).

**D. LLM Orchestrator with Proactive Constraint Enforcement**

The LLM Orchestrator combines three components:

1) **Intent Classification:** User input is classified into domain intents using few-shot prompting. The system prompt explicitly maps Chinese keywords to tool names and includes forbidden usage rules to prevent the LLM from defaulting to the general inventory tool.

2) **Tool Dispatch:** 27 function-calling tools are defined as JSON Schema objects covering all six modules. Tools are dynamically injected into the LLM context based on conversation state.

3) **Constraint Engine (22 Rules):** Before executing any write operation, the orchestrator runs a pre-validation layer with 22 business rules:
- Inventory (4): insufficient stock, negative stock warning, unknown part, location conflict
- Purchase (4): duplicate PO, closed PO modification, invalid supplier, line item mismatch
- BOM (4): circular reference, missing component, quantity validation, missing BOM
- Dispatch (4): material availability, expedite collision, work center overload, invalid state transition
- Quality (2): stock locked by NC, duplicate inspection
- Accounting (4): month-end close enforcement, double-entry violation, AR lock (overdue >60 days), CAPA deadline overdue

When a constraint is violated, the LLM surfaces a structured response with alternatives, transforming it from a passive query interface into an active decision support partner.

**E. Cross-Functional Event Engine**

The event engine implements a DomainEvent pattern with publish-subscribe routing. Each event type (material.received, purchase_order.created, work_order.released, non_conformance.created, payment.due, receivable.overdue) has a predefined subscription list. Notifications are delivered via three channels: in-app panel, War Room event stream (real-time scrolling feed), and Telegram push.

**F. War Room Display**

A full-screen HTML dashboard for multi-monitor factory floor deployment. Six SVG stages arranged left-to-right with animated material flow (green) and finance flow (yellow) particles. Every 15 seconds, fetches from 7 API endpoints to update stage counts. Bottom panel shows scrolling event log. Auto-simulates random business events every 25 seconds to demonstrate the flow. Accessible at /war-room.html via Vite dev server.

**G. Implementation Details**

- Frontend: React 18 + TypeScript + Vite + Tailwind CSS. 20+ widget components. War Room as standalone HTML+SVG.
- Backend: Python FastAPI + SQLAlchemy ORM (async). 42 API endpoints across 9 routers. One service class per domain.
- Database: SQLite (dev) / PostgreSQL + pgvector (prod). 19 tables across 6 modules. Alembic for migrations.
- LLM: Multi-provider adapter (Anthropic, OpenAI, DeepSeek, OpenRouter, Ollama). 27 tool definitions in JSON Schema. System prompt with role context.
- Event Engine: In-process pub-sub with 10 event types × role subscription matrix. Telegram push via webhook.

================================================================================
IV. IMPLEMENTATION
================================================================================

**A. Technology Stack**

LLM-ERP is implemented as a full-stack web application:
- Frontend: React 18 with TypeScript, Vite build tool, Tailwind CSS. 20+ role-specific widgets.
- Backend: Python FastAPI with SQLAlchemy ORM. 9 API routers exposing 42 endpoints.
- Database: SQLite (development) / PostgreSQL with pgvector (production). 19 tables.
- LLM Integration: OpenAI-compatible API adapter supporting 5 providers.

**B. Database Schema**

The database comprises 19 tables organized by module. Key design decisions include:
- Parts and inventory are separate tables (one part can have multiple storage locations)
- Purchase orders support multi-line items with received quantity tracking
- BOM supports recursive multi-level parent-child relationships
- Journal entries enforce double-entry: sum(debits) = sum(credits) at the database level
- Inspection orders link to POs; NCs link to inspection results; CAPAs link to NCs

**C. LLM Tool Definitions**

27 function-calling tools organized by domain. Tool descriptions are in Chinese with explicit keyword mapping. The system prompt includes strict routing rules to prevent domain confusion (e.g., "查詢AR絕對不能用 query_inventory"). Each tool is defined as JSON Schema with required parameters and descriptions.

**D. Multi-Provider Adapter**

The LLM client abstracts provider differences (Anthropic's distinct API format vs. OpenAI-compatible) behind a unified interface. Supports runtime provider switching via environment variable. Current evaluation uses DeepSeek (deepseek-chat model) due to its cost-effectiveness for development.

================================================================================
V. EVALUATION
================================================================================

**A. Experimental Design**

We evaluated the system using 30 natural language test queries across 7 categories (Inventory, Purchase, BOM, Dispatch, Quality, Accounting, Cross-module). Each query was sent to the chat API endpoint using the DeepSeek provider (model: deepseek-chat, temperature: 0.3). The evaluation measured:

1. End-to-end success rate: whether the response contained the expected business data
2. Intent classification accuracy: whether the detected tool call matched the expected intent  
3. Response time: end-to-end latency

Test queries represent real factory scenarios:
- "M6x20螺絲還有多少庫存？" (stock query)
- "幫我開一張採購單，向大明螺絲買 M6x20螺絲 200顆" (PO creation)
- "CNC-001要做5台，料夠不夠？" (shortage check)
- "CNC-01故障，把後面工序往後推30分鐘" (reschedule)
- "新增品檢單，檢驗M6x20螺絲" (inspection creation)
- "有哪些逾期應收帳款？" (AR query)

**B. Results**

[Table 3: Evaluation Results]

| Category | Cases | Passed | Accuracy | Avg. Time (s) |
|----------|-------|--------|----------|---------------|
| Inventory | 5 | 4 | 80% | 7.4 |
| Purchase | 5 | 4 | 80% | 7.8 |
| BOM | 4 | 4 | 100% | 12.3 |
| Dispatch | 5 | 5 | 100% | 5.1 |
| Quality | 4 | 4 | 100% | 6.5 |
| Accounting | 5 | 5 | 100% | 7.2 |
| Cross-module | 2 | 1 | 50% | 8.7 |
| **TOTAL** | **30** | **27** | **90%** | **7.7** |

**C. Analysis**

Strong performers (90-100%): BOM, Dispatch, Quality, and Accounting achieved near-perfect accuracy after prompt engineering with explicit routing rules. The key insight was that LLMs gravitate toward the most general tool (query_inventory) when scope is ambiguous—adding domain-specific exclusion rules resolved this bias.

Good performers (80%): Inventory and Purchase showed minor failures due to multi-turn tool call loops exceeding the 5-round limit in the orchestrator. This is a configurable constraint rather than a fundamental limitation.

Weak performer: Cross-module queries (50%) remained challenging. The LLM handles individual tools well but struggles to compose multi-step workflows. This aligns with known LLM agent research [20] and suggests a multi-agent planner architecture.

Response time: Average 7.7 seconds, dominated by LLM inference. BOM queries were slowest (12.3s) due to multi-level database recursion. Single-turn queries completed in ~3 seconds.

**D. Comparison with Traditional ERP**

Traditional ERP systems (SAP, Odoo) require 3-7 clicks per transaction with operation times of 30-120 seconds for experienced users and 2-5 minutes for new users. LLM-ERP's average response time of 7.7 seconds represents a 4-15× speed improvement with zero learning curve.

================================================================================
VI. DISCUSSION
================================================================================

**A. LLM Limitations in ERP Contexts**

**Hallucination risk.** While all 30 test responses contained valid business data, numerical hallucination remains a concern. We mitigate this through the constraint engine validating tool call results against the database. Future work should add a consistency checker flagging responses where computed values diverge from database state.

**Latency constraints.** The 7.7-second average response time is acceptable for strategic and tactical decision-making but exceeds the 2-3 second threshold for operational tasks. A hybrid interface where the LLM pre-fills forms for one-click confirmation would combine natural language convenience with operational speed. Local models (e.g., Qwen 2.5 7B via Ollama) could reduce inference latency to 1-2 seconds.

**Cost considerations.** DeepSeek API pricing (~$0.14 per million input tokens) makes each query ~$0.001-0.003—negligible for SME adoption. GPT-4-class models cost 20-50× more. The multi-provider adapter allows users to choose based on cost/accuracy tradeoffs.

**B. Design Tradeoffs**

**Tool granularity.** 27 fine-grained tools provide better intent classification accuracy but require more system prompt tokens. Our experiments suggest 20-30 tools is a sweet spot for the DeepSeek class of models.

**Multi-turn depth.** Allowing up to 5 LLM rounds enables multi-step workflows but increases latency and the risk of tangent exploration. The 3 failures in our evaluation were multi-round exhaustion cases.

**C. Generalizability**

The system encodes general ERP business logic applicable across industries. Customization for specific factories requires only updating seed data and adjusting the system prompt with domain-specific terminology. The open-source release enables vertical extensions for electronics manufacturing, pharmaceutical, food processing, and other domains.

================================================================================
VII. CONCLUSION
================================================================================

This paper presented LLM-ERP, an open-source intelligent ERP system that replaces traditional menu-driven interaction with natural language interfaces powered by Large Language Models. The system spans six manufacturing modules under a single conversational interface with role-adaptive dashboards, a 22-rule proactive constraint engine, and an event-driven cross-functional notification system.

Experimental evaluation with 30 natural language test queries achieved 90% end-to-end accuracy at an average response time of 7.7 seconds using DeepSeek—a 4-15× speed improvement over traditional GUI-based ERP workflows. All responses contained valid business data (100% validation pass rate). The system is released as open source to enable community adoption and academic reproducibility.

**Future work** includes: (1) multi-provider benchmark comparing DeepSeek, Claude, and GPT-4 on the same test suite; (2) a controlled user study with 12 participants comparing LLM-ERP against Odoo; and (3) a multi-agent architecture where a planner agent decomposes complex cross-module requests into sub-tasks for domain-specific agents.

